Considering the enormous volume of data transmission bandwidth on the imaging spectrometer’s scientific data downlink, several pixel binning schemes with real-time data processing were adopted for nadir observation, dominated by multi-sample hyperspectral mode and multispectral imaging mode. According to the highly elliptical orbit designed for remote sensing, nadir detection will be conducted in a continuously varying scheme dependent on orbital altitude, as shown in Fig. 4. At periapsis, the orbital altitude will reach a minimum of 265 km, an altitude of less than 800 km, and the effective detection time per orbit will be approximately 26 minutes. Supported by its capability of 0.5 mrad IFOV and 416 samples cell array for nadir observation, the swath width of MMS is ∼55km\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
